{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17616522","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17616522"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:04:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:04:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16397"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16397","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16397"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0,0.88,0.03,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9088"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74643"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9088","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9088"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16397"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60137"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5937"},{"type":"tags","id":"7117"},{"type":"tags","id":"10387"},{"type":"tags","id":"10388"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21592"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21593"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74643","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74643"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 57-year-old gentleman presents with his wife to the neurosurgery clinic for a routine followup. He suffered a severe traumatic brain injury 2 years ago. You have been asked by the registrar to speak with the gentleman and have found that he is able to respond to your questions confidently and fluently, however his responses make no sense, even using new words that don\u0027t exist.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most characteristic of Wernicke\u0027s aphasia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decreased fluency of speech","Preserved comprehension","Fluent but meaningless speech","Marked frustration with communication","Associated dysarthria"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a typical picture of Wernicke\u0027s aphasia, which occurs due to damage to the posterior superior temporal gyrus in the dominant (usually left) hemisphere. The key feature is fluent but meaningless speech with impaired comprehension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFluent but meaningless speech\u003C/strong\u003E is the hallmark of Wernicke\u0027s aphasia. Patients produce grammatically correct sentences with normal rhythm and intonation, but the content lacks meaning and often contains nonsense words (neologisms) or inappropriate word substitutions (paraphasias).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased fluency\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of Broca\u0027s aphasia, not Wernicke\u0027s aphasia. In Broca\u0027s aphasia, speech is non-fluent, effortful, and telegraphic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPreserved comprehension\u003C/strong\u003E is not a feature of Wernicke\u0027s aphasia. These patients typically have severely impaired comprehension of both spoken and written language.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMarked frustration\u003C/strong\u003E is more commonly seen in Broca\u0027s aphasia. Wernicke\u0027s aphasia patients often lack awareness of their deficit (anosognosia) and therefore show little frustration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDysarthria\u003C/strong\u003E is a motor speech disorder affecting articulation and is not a feature of Wernicke\u0027s aphasia. It can occur with other types of stroke but is separate from aphasia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of Wernicke\u0027s aphasia focuses on identifying and treating the underlying cause (commonly stroke) and initiating speech and language therapy. The prognosis varies but is generally poorer than for Broca\u0027s aphasia, particularly if comprehension remains severely impaired.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Wernicke\u0027s aphasia is characterised by fluent but meaningless speech with poor comprehension.","Patients with Wernicke\u0027s aphasia often lack awareness of their language deficit.","Wernicke\u0027s aphasia results from damage to the posterior superior temporal gyrus in the dominant hemisphere."],"references":["Binder JR. The Wernicke area: Modern evidence and a reinterpretation. Neurology. 2015 Dec 15;85(24):2170-5. doi: 10.1212/WNL.0000000000002219. Epub 2015 Nov 13. PMID: 26567270; PMCID: PMC4691684.","Hartman K, Peluzzo A, Shadani S, Chellquist I, Weprin S, Hunt H, Smith-Benjamin S, Altschuler EL. Devising a Method to Study if Wernicke\u0027s Aphasia Patients are Aware That They Do Not Comprehend Language or Speak It Understandably. J Undergrad Neurosci Educ. 2017 Nov 15;16(1):E5-E12. PMID: 29371852; PMCID: PMC5777850.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60137"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16397"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60137","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60137"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-26T10:26:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T07:42:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9088"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id